Modeling Health Data with Random Forest Classification¶

Complete by: Tuesday 1 Apr. at class time
Data: https://jrladd.com/CIS241/data/500_Cities_small.csv

What does it mean for a place to be healthy? What can we learn about the overall health of people in the United States by looking at health by city and locality? These are the questions that the CDC's PLACES project attempts to answer. This project originally began in 2015 as the "500 Cities Project": an annual survey of the 500 largest cities in the US. By surveying these cities every year, the CDC hopes to better understand long-term health among Americans all across the country.

As we continue through the COVID-19 pandemic, data analysis focused on health and healthcare continues to be at the center of public conversation. Good data analysis in this domain is essential for public health in the 21st century. In this week's workshop, you'll examine recent data from the PLACES project to better understand American's overall health.

*For this workshop, you will make a coherent and readable report. As you go through each section, make sure you are explaining, describing and interpreting all code, visualizations, and statistical output. The goal is that a reader with no previous knowledge of the data should be able to understand your findings.*

Exploring Data with Decision Trees¶

While a random forest approach is best for accurate classification overall, individual decision trees are useful for exploring the data and understanding how variables interact.

  • Import the necessary libraries. Which parts of sklearn will you need? What won't you need?
  • Read the data as a CSV using the link above.
  • Using sklearn's DecisionTreeRegressor, fit a decision tree model to the data set. Use Physical Health as your target.
  • Keep in mind all the steps that will go into this: preparing and splitting the data, standardizing the data, and fitting the model.
  • Create a visualization of the decision tree. It should look like this one (the Penguins example from Tuesday):

  • Sci-kit learn has a built-in function to make these tree diagrams. Make sure it has colors and labels for each variable, just like the example above. You'll also need to make the figure size larger to make this readable.
  • Find the feature importances for your decision tree.
  • Write an interpetation of your decision tree. What does it tell you about the relationships between your variables? Which variables seem most important? Will this help you determine hyperparameters when you fit your random forest regressorr?

Random Forest Regression¶

Once again what we want to know is: how healthy are people in different cities overall? If we had information on a new city, could we predict how healthy the people in that city might be?

  • Use Physical Health as your target variable. This variable does *not* indicate that people are healthy. Write down what this variable actually means. You can check the PLACES documentation that I linked to above.
  • Next choose some predictor variables. Use the decision tree diagram above to help you narrow down which predictors to use. Remember, if you use categorical variables that will generate hundreds of columns in your one-hot encoded data, that will slow down your model and likely cause your kernel to overload!
  • Run a Random Forest regression using these predictors and targets. Make sure you've scaled the variables and done all appropriate pre-processing. Explain your steps and interpret the results fully.
  • Use out-of-sample validation to check your model's residuals and calculate some appropriate measures. How did your model perform? How did it compare to the KNN regression you ran last time?

Classifying Data with the Random Forest¶

We still want to know if the health of people in certain cities varies strongly by state. Given information about a new city, could we correctly predict the state in which it's located? Let's see if we can get better results with the Random Forest than we did with KNN.

  • Use StateAbbr as your target. But there are too many states to reasonably interpret the results. As you did last time, narrow it down to just the two states with more than 40 cities in our data.
  • Before you begin modeling, create a decision tree diagram for your classifier just like you did for the regressor above. Interpret the diagram fully and choose your predictor variables based on what the diagram tells you.
  • Run a Random Forest classification using your chosen predictors and target. Make sure you've scaled the variables and done all appropriate pre-processing. Explain your steps and interpret the results fully.
  • Find the variable importance of each predictor. Interpret these fully. Which variables were most important and why? Did this surprise you or not, based on what you learned from the decision tree?
  • Use out-of-sample validation to check your model's confusion matrix, calculate appropriate measures, cross-validate, and make some visualizations. How well did your model perform? How did it compare to the KNN classifier from last time? (Keep in mind that we couldn't do an ROC curve on Tuesday because we didn't have a binary classifier, but this classifier will be binary.)

Write a brief summary of what you learned about American cities through this analysis. Did your random forest models perform better than KNN? Why or why not? What other approaches might you recommend? Is there additional data on cities that you might want to add to this analyis?

In [5]:
health = health.dropna(subset = predictors + [target])
X=health[predictors]
y=health[target]
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, 
    y, 
    test_size=0.3, 
    random_state=42)

This line of code assigns the predictors to the X variable and the target to the y for the decision tree model. This code also splits the data into training and testing portions.

In [6]:
plt.figure(figsize = [50, 25])
reg = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_leaf_nodes=12, min_samples_leaf=3,criterion="squared_error",random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)
feature_names = reg.feature_names_in_
plot_tree(reg, filled=True, fontsize = 20, feature_names = feature_names, class_names=y)
plt.title("Decision tree trained on important health features")
plt.show()

This line of code creates the decision tree based on the predictor and target variables. Beginning of the top of the decision tree, we begin with the High Blood Pressure variable. If a high number of people have high blood pressure, this connects the relationship to Obesity as a second predictor of poor physical health. If a high proportion of people have both high cholesterol levels and obesity, we can assume they have poor physical health. If there is no correlation between high blood pressure and obesity, then the decision tree begins a new line of correlation between high blood pressure and cholesterol screening. Thus, there is a high connection between high blood pressure and high cholesterol levels, so we can assume that an individual with both variables have poor physical health. High proportions of individuals with high blood pressure have a strong correlation to both high proportions of obesity and/or high proportions of high cholesterol levels.

If a small proportion of individuals have high blood pressure, the tree checks for high proportions of individuals with a lack of sleep. If a high proportion of these individuals lack sleep, the tree checks for a correlation to a high proportion of individuals with high cholesterol levels. If there is a high enough proportion of individuals with lack of sleep and high proportion of high cholesterol levels, one can assume these individuals have poor phyiscal health.

Contrary to one's assumptions, the health dataset checks for the proportion of people who do not have the ability to function properly, engage in physical activity, and maintain a healthy lifestyle.

plt.show()

This decision tree begins with its first variable as Physical Inactivity. Because of this, I can assume that Physical Inactivity will be an important feature for my random forest. Based on the decision, this model predicts that a high number of individuals with lack of activity will be located in Texas. Conversely, this means that a low proportion of individuals with a lack of physical activity are located in California. However, if between 22 - 29% of individuals lack physical activity, the decision tree then checks for the proportion of people who currently smoke. After determining which proportion of people from a particular state are phyiscally inactive, the decision tree begins to determine a correlation between Current Smoking and Physical Inactivity. The decision tree continues to determine correlation between Physical Inactivity and Smoking; it predicts that most individuals with a lack of physical activity but a higher proportion of smoking live in California.

After the decision tree detects no correlation between lack of physical activity and smoking, it then checks for a correlation between Physical Inactivity and High Cholesterol. If the proportion of Physical Inactivity is high enough, the decision tree predicts that these individuals live in Texas. Otherwise, it then checks for individuals who are physically active but have high cholesterol. If the proportionality of individuals who have high cholesterol is large enough, the tree predicts that these individuals live in California, and live in Texas otherwise.

Lastly, Obesity plays a limited factor in this decision tree, meaning that it is not an important feature for my random forest model.

Because Physical Inactivity and Current Smoking are located near the top of the decision tree, they will be the predictors for my random forest classifier model, and is shown in the line of code below.
